Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment: So sound and a shotgun accomplished what a Bradley Main Battle Tank and various other deadly machines of war somehow mysteriously could NOT accomplish?? Really?? What about the fighter pilots in the air? What about the Navy at sea? Not to mention under the sea? How were those particular forces eradicated?? Come on! It was a fun enough movie, I really DID enjoy it and almost cried when the little ankle biter was killed playing with his noisy space shuttle. I guess I really wanted some stab at an explanation as to why all of the worlds various armed forces, with their variety of very powerful weapons of war, not to mention trained soldiers, just why they couldn't accomplish with what they had, what apparently a farm wife with a friggin mere shotgun and sound COULD accomplish. Even a generic explanation added to the script would have been cool. Still a good movie and I would recommend

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
One of my favorite movies of 2018 with Mandy being my number one favorite! My second fave horror film of 2018 after Mandy! this movie should be a wake up call to the mainstream horror genre to get out of the shitter!¬†

The mainsteam is to take a page from the independent studios and independent horror films and foreign horror¬†films with stuff like It Follows, Housebound, The Babadook, Tragedy Girls etc. stop remaking great horror films that don't need to be remade like Poltergeist, stop making sequels to worn out horror franchises, stop prequels etc.

independent horror films are out from the shitter known as mainstream when the mainstream should get out of the shitter, look for independent or foreign and say "screw the mainstream" sometimes as there is surprises like A Quiet Place to Get Out etc. and when i'm talking mainstream i mean shit like Poltergeist remake which thankfully bombed and Insidious 4 which didn't do well and dunno why Ouiji a hit, i'm glad people went to see It Follows and some people support that. Enough too much PG-13 stuff like Ouiji but A Quiet Place was excellent for a PG-13 horror film.

Remake little known films like Blood Beach or Lifeforce rather than classics like Poltergeist which thankfully bombed as it's forgotten about where the original will always be remembered but Suspiria looks nice and should be a good remake that is trying something different than be a xerox copy like Poltergeist. They need risks again, take it again mainstream just like the independents are! Paranormal Activity wasn't a risk, stop with the ghost movies, stop with the found footage movies and do something different in the mainstream horror genre. Take a page from It Follows and more. Stop being lazy mainstream horror genre, get off your fat ass and put down the potato chips or twinkies shoving and shoving them in your mouth and do something else, start trying to do something unique. Just try something different than another remake of a great movie like Poltergeist, sequel to an older franchise, found footage and all that. I don't get the hype and praise Halloween 2018 is getting! A Quiet Place was a much better 2018 horror film than that cashgrab sequel Halloween as it was something different, it took risks and became a box-office hit as i welcome it and i welcome the upcoming sequel as this is a new fresh franchise i want to embrace.

i just don't want to see these horror icons (Jason, Freddy, Chucky, Ghostface, Michael, Leatherface, Jigsaw) over and over again on the big screen and your just gonna get diminishing returns just like the Universal monsters being ran into the ground in the 30s/40s/50s as they had huge characters and big hits on their hands then pumped out sequel after another (the only great sequel is Bride of Frankenstein) and the bottom completely fell out with diminishing box-office returns and before these characters became jokes even with Abbot and Costello movies then Universal knew when to quit. If Halloween 2018 becomes a hit then studios will be like "audiences want more Halloween, they want more Candyman, more Freddy, Jason Voorhees etc.", but for Candyman, one Candyman movie was enough as the first was excellent but the sequels were cash-ins and no more Elm Street films, Robert IS Freddy as Jackie proved it was a failure to recast Freddy for you can't do it, Robert IS the character and always was as even Englund said so.

Can't we have new horror icons already? let the worn out old tired icons like Freddy, Michael, Jason, Leatherface, Jigsaw, Ghostface, Candyman, Chucky and Pinhead die and rest in peace already, don't keep digging up them from their graves every 5 or 10 or 15 years then propping their corpses up on the big screen in Weekend at Bernies style. Just come up with with your own new horror icon and new horror franchise already! i'm not a big fan of Insidious and the Conjuring spin-offs but at least it's something different, well not quite different, but not the same old horror franchise some of us seen or the same horror icons for they are trying to create their own. I know they haven't been the best but at least they are giving a shit and giving it an effort, that's just how i feel about it.

Just try try again mainstream horror genre! making new horror icons would actually work because there are no ideas to bring in for most horror icons. New horror icons might get the hate, but it may take time before the newer ones would gain praise. I'll say this though. Even though using the same stuff is unnecessary. Just like in the last decade we got new horror icons in the mainstream like the Creeper, Captain Splauding and Jigsaw while Sam from Trick R Treat becomes a cult horror icon with Leslie Vernon when Trick and Behind the Mask were sent to the DVD direct to video market rather than to all mainstream theaters which should had happened even Hatchet was shown in midnight theaters than all theaters as there's Victor Crawley whom is a cult horror icon.

Now outside the mainstream we got Wolfcop, Tucker and Dale etc. should had been released in all theaters. I'd say end these horror franchises (Chucky/Halloween/Elm Street/Friday The 13th/Saw/Scream/Hellraiser/Texas Chainsaw Massacre) and bury them, let them rest in peace from film and let them live on through merchandise, comics, video games, toys, appreal, streams of the old movies on amazon/hulu/crackle/Netflix whatever even re-issues of the films on blu-ray and that's fair game.

Can we have new original cinematic horror icons/new franchises already? try to come up with new horror icons/franchises and try try again mainstream and let the older franchises rest in peace in favor of new franchises/new icons. This one has an excellent script, solid performances, emotion, nice creature effects and quality ideas.

This is precisely what i want in mainstream horror genre. Something different and fresh. Something different to take risks again, i want Hollywood and mainstream horror genre to take risk again and learn from this.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
I loved this movie!  

I thought 2018 would be the year for horror movies, but a lot of them sucked major balls like Halloween, The Nun, Jigsaw, Jeepers Creepers, Slenderman. I was really looking forward for The New Mutants, but that was held back another year. So, another disappointment. All in all, lots of sucky movies, but this one was actually good. 

I don‚Äôt know why people say that this film has a lot of plot-holes because it really doesn‚Äôt. I mean yea, they could have lived by a river/waterfall, but that would make mean that they would be out in the open. Maybe they wanted to live in a traditional home. Also, another thing the reason why the mom couldn‚Äôt give birth in the soundproof room is because she was being hunted by that creature. So, that isn‚Äôt a plot-hole. You try to get into another room while you‚Äôre giving birth and while  you‚Äôre being hunted, it‚Äôs not that easy, lol. It seems easy because it‚Äôs all in the same house, but it‚Äôs not. Also, it‚Äôs not like she could have walked to the river/waterfall. On top of that the soundproof room didn‚Äôt really work.  It lasted like one night. Apparently you can make or find soundproof rooms super easy according to bloggers and commenters that were finding plot-holes. But, if this were to really happen I highly doubt that. Good example is the soundproof room dying after one night. 

So, I don‚Äôt think it had plot-holes. It was interesting though that the solution to fighting off the creatures was super sonic sounds. That just seems kind of stupid to me. Because they relay on sound so much, so I would think they would be tolerant to high pitch sound. Kind of like how bats are. You know how bats are kind of  blind, but they are really good with sounds? Well, they‚Äôre also tolerate to high pitch sounds. So, I guess that‚Äôs the one plot-hole, but considering we know nothing about these creatures, we can‚Äôt say anything abut the science of these creatures. 

All in all, I really like this movie.

Comment:
*While this is a 'fresh' and 'unique' concept... there are still some things thay needs explanation.*

- Are the aliens attracted to all kinds of sounds?... if so, then why don't they go to the waterfall? or Do they attack trees when the wind causes the branches to rattle?

- If the aliens are blind, then how did they find their way to Earth?

- If the aliens were blind then wouldn't that make their sense of smell extra heightened as well?... aside from their hearing. 

- Where are all of our armies and weapons? (Bombs, Drones, Guns, Tanks, etc).

- I also highly doubt that anyone can live that long without making a single sound. (Sneezing, Coughing, etc)... these things are bound to happen.

- And lastly, I think that it was so dumb of the couple to have a new baby, since babies are noisy and cry a lot.

*There's just a lot of questions!!!*

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment: This movie was one of the most stupid I've ever seen. Literally. It's so full of mistakes and everyone in the movie behaves like they have no brains at all, so the only enjoyment is watching them die. For example, they haven't made their house soundproofed. Instead they keep all their doors open all year around. Eventually the husband gets the clever idea of using old newspapers as soundproofing, even though the problem had been around for several years. He can build a freaking hearing aid, but didn't ever before consider that. Nothing they do makes any sense, even in small scale, like the nail they've for some reason left sticking out their stairs so that somebody can conveniently step on it. The movie is also full of contradictions in it's inner coherence, e.g. the creatures can easily hear even the smallest creaks from miles away, but they can't hear people breathing or their heartbeats even if they stand right next to them. There are tons of other similar mistakes, but I'm not going to dwell on them.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
A Quiet Place is a brilliant allegory referencing today's political atmosphere where politically correct leftist viciously hunts down and eradicates any decent, noise. In the movie, we see that society has succumbed to the tactics of the monsters and learned to remain silent at all times. It isn't until society, portrayed by the film's family finds its voice that they can fight back. By standing their ground in the face of the monster or politically correct leftists that society uses a stronger sound, Trump, to bring down the beast. 

Aside from the obvious allegory to today's culture in the United States, it's a great horror flick that doesn't require low budget gore to deliver an intense ride.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
This movie is a perfect allegory for totalitarian government.  Silence becomes the safe tower. To bite one's own tongue is more precious than a bullet proof vest.  High amounts of both glee or pain register as a threat.  

I find it interesting when Emily Blunt steps on the protruding nail.   It calls to mind the eastern idiom of a nail that sticks out being hammered (not drunk, that's Emily's other movie).  I know this is probably a stretch, but when Blunt is trying to keep quiet during child birth my mind goes to China's one child policy.  Silence plays powerfully as secrecy.

The fireworks conjures up images of an independence day celebration.   The boisterous and gaudy display of freedom relishes in being marvelously conspicuous.

The monsters are a stand-in for any abuse of power really.  Any oppressive situation can wedge itself into this template: domestic violence typified by a fearfully quiet wife, a powerful corporation that compels you to keep their secrets, and religious or scientific orthodoxy that will ruin you if you speak contrary to their wisdom put a chill in us.

I like the concept of a loud natural sound being a bubble of protection.  This loud natural noise seems to to be a blunt truth.  C'mon you knew it was coming.  Seriously though, the supreme leader can not kill a scientist for telling him they don't have enough enriched uranium to make a nuke.  Even a cruel dictator must bow before reality.  

I'm just waiting for memes where Dwight Shrut is the monster that kills Jim.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
the movie is... okay. interesting. not at all scary. okay. but also stupid. and some shit isn't explained and clear. like what about sneezing, farting, your shit hitting the water in the toilette, accidentally screaming (because you got scared or hurt), laughing - things we can't really control? and they can walk around and make sounds with other stuff buf can't even whisper? (yes I know they whispered in one or two scenes maybe but all of the other times they rely mostly on sign language)
also, WTAF is wrong with these "parents". like, they walked god knows how many miles in the beginning of the movie and the youngest of their children was left to walk the last, behind all of them. even if it wasn't a post apocalyptic scenario, that is really dangerous. like, shit can happen to a fucking 4yo if you don't pay attention. you put the children in front of you goddamnit, so you see at all times what's going on. cause they should be more important than you, right? 
then the getting pregnant part. like a lot of people already said - that's just really shitty. use a fucking condom, morons. not only is the world going to be a dangerous place for the baby but also, the baby is going to be dangerous for the world. babies communicate by fucking. crying. out. loud., legit. screaming. and still, the shit parents decide to boink without protection, not giving a shit about the danger they're bringing themselves, their children and their newborn in. like... the fuck seriously. especially after they already lost one child goddamnit. how bout keeping it in your pants for the sake of surviving... smh. ALSO, if I get a "she was pregnant before the aliens came" comment, you can suck right on it because she fucking wasn't. first day was 80 something and the aliens were already there AND KILLED THEIR SON. next day was 471 and she was pregnant. do the math guys. 470 days is a year and a half. can't be pregnant for that long. okay.
also, when the father send his, what, 6-7yo son to light up some fireworks what the fuck lel? there are some weird killing creatures walking around and he sends his kid to do a preeetty adult job and risks having him killed, either by the fireworks or by the aliens, to go check up on the wife. I mean. what. okay, yes, she's pregnant and all but you can't leave your son like that in such a dangerous situation. and then he reaches the wife, meanwhile noone heard or saw their daughter in hours and the son is god knows where after firing the rockets. do they care? the wife is fine, the basement is sound secure, everything's okay with the world and the wife and the baby BUT WHERE ARE YOUR OTHER TWO CHILDREN. instead of rushing out TO FIND THEM, the parents TALK about having to protect them. WHAT. they are KIDS, GTFO AND FIND THEM YOU MORONIC FATHER. and then he goes and is all chill and walking slow and shit. I'd run around like a crazy mofo if my kids were in danger. and I don't even have kids. I have a dog. I would do that for my dog. nope, my dog OR my children would never even wind up in a situation like that, wouldn't allow it. you don't have to be slow, you have to be quiet. skip around, I don't give a shit, just hurry and get your fucking kids before you lose them too. idiots.
so yeah now that I've covered the shitty parents part, I also want to ask, if there's someone smart enough to tell me about the fucking nail in the stair. that was sooo random, so randomly inserted into the movie to make it more dramatic but it's stupid as fuck, like, obviously the nail wasn't always there so how did it show up all of a sudden, and of course, oh so conviniently? makes. no. sense. also, when the stupid mother was dragging the bag that got caught on to the nail, she wasn't fucking smart enough to look why the bag stopped moving but instead she kept tugging on it? CMOOON. noone with even just a bit of brains would do that. if she did what any normal person would do, she never would have stepped on it. obviously. moron.

cheers.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment: While I did enjoy this movie, it was not as good as its' predecessor- the other social thriller from 2017 "Get Out". Whereas Get Out's social commentary focused on racism, the theme here in a Quiet Place was the "family" and protecting your family at all costs. The movie started out slowly and picked up in the middle, it didn't feel much intense, but makes up for those shortcomings with the blood and gore in the movie. It's also not a complete silent movie, which is good. The weakness for the monsters wasn't well thought out, and the ending could've been better. There is intense music which alerts you when you need pay attention to the screen, they'll be a few times when you aren't paying attention because nothing's happening and there's no talking going on and the director knows some of us won't be focusing on the screen so they use the intense music to draw us in. I also think there's a problem with sub-standard writing- in some scenes the movie was all over the place, hoping quickly from one scene to another with little explanation given for of the characters decisions. The biggest flaw, imo, is the movie didn't attempt to explain where or why the aliens are here or where they came from, or what they are ie- aliens, monsters, demons, etc. 5/10 C. A tad bit overrated, but worthwhile.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
What a pointless piece of crap. I don't see how the people lived as long as they did given how inept they were.
***************** Spoilers Ahead ****************************


The father didn't bother to take his shotgun wherever he went. Not even an ax. It's especially bad that he didn't take it when he went looking for the kids at the end. But then I guess they would not have a reason to show his self sacrifice at the end. Also pointless. He didn't even try to take a swing at the thing with the ax. And the greatest minds on the planet couldn't figure out that a creature with super sensitive hearing might be incapacitated by high frequency sound at high volume? The girl and wife just happened to stumble on that at the last minute. Yeah right. Pretty much as crappy an ending as "Signs" where the guy discovers the aliens can be killed with water. I mean, they invade a planet 75% covered with water (it even falls from the sky) and don't even bother to wear a raincoat? Comment:
This film represents what happens when the internal logic of a film reaches epic fail proportions. Without going into spoilers this film sets a premise that the characters are incapable of achieving.

Look at zombie movies and series...any modern film or series that shows characters shooting zombies ANYWHERE but in the head is an epic fail. It's like as if the characters had never lived in a world that ever had a film or series about zombies meaning...get the point? It would be common knowledge to many people especially those who managed to live 90 days or more. You get smart or you get dead.

Where this film starts doesn't match what you see in the film. The events of the film make no sense.

This problem occurs in many films, especially these types of films.

Save your time and money...you can thank me later.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
It's shit! Utter tripe of a movie. I saw it the last day it was in cinemas, thought I'd check it out due to the glowing reviews the movie received but the critics must have seen an entirely different film! 
 
I usually like turning my mind off during a movie and try to get soaked into the world but the glaring plotholes throughout the entirety of the piece made it unbelievably difficult to do so. 
There's a few problems listed in the comments so I'll try not to repeat them and also not try to spoil anything for you in case it's on Netflix and you're borderline about to stab your hand with a fork to feel something, I'll list a couple out: 

- They live on a farm, a farm that grows corn. How in the world is one supposed to not just plant corn quietly but harvest it too? 
- The boy and girl that fall into the silo of corn sink like one would in quicksand. Corn doesn't displace like fucking sand. The little bastard would have broken his legs falling 30ft into fucking corn. Modern day Scrooge McDuck shit.  
- The waterfall part where the son and father are able to shout. Why not create a homestead there? 
- Speaking of waterfalls, the aliens that have managed to travel to Earth (implying their aliens) with practically no vision, just the power of sound and they can't differentiate a waterfall to human speech?
- This may be the single greatest plothole but the whole premise of fighting them with sound (I don't know if it was meant to be a plot twist because it was transparent as hell from minute 1) is more of a question than answer due to every single country failing to coming up with that solution. I mean, c'mon. They attack due to sound, in nature, one attacks due to a threat; in this case, it's sound. The aliens didn't eat the humans but killed them so it wasn't for sustinence, how fucking difficult can it be, I'm sure the 80 or something days before we're introduced to the family, one would notice that they don't fucking like noise. Could you imagine them in New York or something with all that sound everywhere, they'd trip out. Anyway, Up/Reduce the frequency of pitch and just blare it at the bastards. (Not sure if I'm right here but I'm guessing human's would be unable to hear such a low or high frequency meaning they'd be safe implying it's higher than ultrasound? Sound as a weapon has been a thing since the war, I'm sure the might of a global military could have the bastards killed and dissected by lunch)
- What is the reason of this 'alien race' attacking the world? (Also the art direction of the monsters are priceless, giant human-esque ears? Priceless)
- Fucking SAND? How witty and clever... fuck me
- Not really a plothole but M. Night Shyamalan's 'Signs' is The Usual Suspects compared to this fucking twist 
- What is represented as aliens that have godly hearing can't deal with a defective hearing aid? 
- I've probably written some spoilers but whatever. Did the wife know that the father was dead at the end. Handled it pretty well. 
- As my mother can atest to, childbirth is pretty fucking painful let alone having her foot crucified by that fucking nail during her contractions
- Why bring a child into this environment? Let alone a newborn not crying or burping or whatever upon birth. She brought a newborn into the world with one of those aliens 3 ft away. She and her baby should have been skewered. 
- Not to bring up a patriarchial complex but the mother was strong as hell but still the maiden in distress? She had a silent fucking birth with an alien that will kill her if she makes a noise with a fucking nail lodged in her foot but needs the amazing John Krazinski (actor/director/fucking savior) to protect her? 

Shit, may have gotten a little carried away but honestly I could go on for much longer.
All in all, this was John Kranzinski's selfgratifying wank. You shouldn't waste your time watching this, there's a ton of movie tropes and there's no 'hiding behind the popcorn' moments. Y'think a 
movie that has a premise involving sound could land some seriously atmospheric moments. Not once was I spooked. 

If you want a good low-budget thriller, watch 'The Babadook', that's on Netflix too.

when the dad took the son out to the waterfall and taught him about the fish i thought that part would have more meaning later on in the movie..although it didnt. the son never got much character development as the girl, mom and dad, but still had several scenes dedicated towards him. 

In the end the son is actually in the corner holding the baby while the mother and daughter fend off the monsters and thats about it. I felt the ending should've been different. Like this...(this is just my opinion I'm not saying it HAD to be like this)

So we have the ending they had but skip ahead in years. (Since the movie tend to skip time a lot it would make sense for ''tis to happen). The baby grew up to about a preteen and the son and daughter, were adults at this point. The son would take the boy to the same place his father once took him and would go to the fish just as he did before, when he was the baby's age. Then the baby (preteen now) gets frightened, but the son says "It's alright we're safe here" and done. 

That's it. So the son has a stronger character and all ties meet. This ending scene will show the viewers that the son did learn from his father and will not only strengthen the sons character, but the dead father as well.


But other then that, this was a great movie to experience in the theatre as you felt you were in the same situation as the characters to stay quiet. (Didn't want to be rude to the rest of the people in the theatre)

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Love the below comment by Bishop Robert Barron in that he considers this as the "most unexpectedly  religious films of 2018."

"I went to see A Quiet Place, John Krasinski‚Äôs new thriller, with absolutely no anticipation of finding theological or spiritual themes. I just wanted a fun evening at the movies. How wonderful when a film surprises you! I don‚Äôt know if I can find the golden thread that draws all of these themes together into a coherent message, but I think one would have to be blind not to see a number of religious motifs in this absorbing film.

The basic structure of the narrative is laid out in simple, deft strokes. We learn that a terrible plague of fierce, devouring creatures has descended on the earth. Where are the monsters from? Outer space, maybe? We‚Äôre never told‚Äîwhich makes the story more compelling. The few people who have survived the holocaust have learned that the creatures, though blind, are extraordinarily acute of hearing. Therefore, the key to survival is silence. Our attention becomes focused on the Abbot family, two youthful parents and three small children, making their quiet way through a beautiful but dangerous open country. When the youngest of the kids flips a switch on his toy rocket, causing buzzing sound to pierce the silence, one of the beasts devours him just before his terrified father can save him. 

We flash-forward several months later, and we watch the Abbots (can the name have possibly been accidental?) going about their lives in what could only be characterized as a monastic manner: no conversations above a whisper, elaborate sign language, quiet work at books and in the fields, silent but obviously fervent prayer before the evening meal, etc. (I will confess that this last gesture, so thoroughly absent from movies and television today, startled me.) Given the awful demands of the moment, any gadgets, machines, electronic entertainment, or noisy implements are out of the question. Their farming is by hand; their fishing is done with pre-modern equipment; even their walking about is done barefoot. And what is most marvelous to behold is that, in this prayerful, quiet, pre-modern atmosphere, even with the threat of imminent death constantly looming, a generous and mutually self-sacrificing family flourishes. The parents care for and protect their children, and the remaining brother and sister are solicitous toward one another and toward their parents. The young girl even regularly risks her life to pay silent tribute to her fallen brother at the spot where he was killed.

Monsters and beasts in the more reflective horror movies are evocative of those things that frighten us the most: illness, failure, our own wickedness, death itself. How wonderful that a Hollywood movie would suggest that what is needed to keep the darkness at bay in our time is silence, simplicity, a return to the earth, prayer, and care for one another. 

The central drama of A Quiet Place is that Mrs. Abbott is expecting a child. The entire family realizes, of course, that a wailing infant would, given the circumstances, mean almost certain death for all of them. And yet, they decide not to kill the child at his birth but to hide him and mute his cries in various ways. When so many in our culture are willing to murder their children for the flimsiest of reasons, when the law gives full protection even to partial-birth abortion, when people blithely say that they would never bring a baby into such a terrible world, the monastic family in this film welcomes life, even into the worst of worlds, and even when such an act is of supreme danger to them. As the baby is coming into the light, the mother finds herself alone (watch the film for the details) and in the most vulnerable situation, for one of the beasts has made its way into their house. As she labors to give birth, the devouring animal lurks. I was put immediately in mind of the scene in the book of Revelation, where Mary is in the throes of child birth as the dragon patiently waits to consume the child. 

As the abbess is struggling to give birth, the abbot has gone in search of his endangered children. He finds them, to his horror, trapped in an abandoned car, one of the beasts clawing at them through the roof, like the T-Rex in Jurassic Park. After mouthing the words, ‚ÄúI love you; I have always loved you‚Äù to his daughter, who gapes at him through the car window, the father screams, drawing the monster to himself. This act of self-emptying love, which serves to liberate his children from danger, is beautifully evocative of the speculations of the Church Fathers regarding the death of Jesus. In his act of self-sacrifice on the cross, the fathers argued, Jesus lured the dark powers into the open and away from the human beings who had been in their thrall. Along similar lines, in an odd working of plot or Providence that can be likened to the efficacy of Christ's sacrifice, it becomes clear in the wake of the father's death that he has left behind for his family the means by which the monsters can be defeated.

I have no real idea whether any or all of this was in the mind of the filmmaker, but I do know from John Krasinski‚Äôs Wikipedia page that he is the son of a Polish-Catholic father and an Irish-Catholic mother and that he was raised a devout practicer of his faith. So until definitively shown otherwise, I am going to maintain that A Quiet Place is the most unexpectedly religious film of 2018."

This movie sucked so bad, I can't believe it!  I was so disappointed in everything.  First of all, they start at, what?, day 89?, the dad carried all of that sand in that stupid little back pack?  And, where the heck did he get it????  I didn't see a beach any where around.  And, they were in a drug store.  Pick up some condoms you big dummy!  If they knew there was a danger, why did they leave the little kid hanging back on the way from the drug store?  Did they want him picked off?????  Why did they only take 1 bottle of pills?  I would have cleaned them out of aspirin and other things, like bandages, antibiotics, etc.  Didn't that water in the tub gurggle on it's way out of the tub after she had the baby?  And, where the heck did that nail come from?  It was a new nail, not an old rusty one.  And, sticking straight up, too!  I've built stairs before, and there was never a nail in the middle of a step!  Why didn't someone step on it before???  Why didn't the mom say something about it?  Nope, she left it there so someone could step on it!  Oh gracious, it was her!  Why didn't it come out of the top of her foot?  It was huge!  I would have screamed my head off!  And, no swelling, infection, or anything????   When the father and son were going in different directions, mom sure didn't look preggers standing outside waving them off.   And, at the end, where the heck did all of that water come from flooding the basement?  And, where did it go, all of a sudden?  Why did she take so long to shoot that thing?  And, when they found out that a high pitched sound killed those things, why didn't they hie down to the local pet store and get some dog whistles?  And, what kind of father is going to leave a mother and 3 children to fend for themselves???  If he was good at building things, i.e., the hearing aid, why couldn't he have made a scarecrow, put in something to make a screeching sound along with a bomb that would go off on impact?  But, of all of the incongruities, that nail really ticks me off!  It was just stupid that it was there and no one stepped on it, EVER, except old mom, and she didn't do a thing about it.  There were so many more, like what's with that old man?  He wasn't necessary to the movie, but these really irritated me.  This movie had some good parts, but it needs a LOT of work to make it a good movie.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
SPOILERS:

I didn't hate it - while OK and kinda original it was kinda stupid. 

1. The monsters have to open up their head armor to hear exposing the soft underparts meaning they can be easily killed with a head shot yet we are to believe these blind stupid clumsy monsters beat the worlds military's?
2. He leaves the shot gun behind for no reason?
3. They have no front door and no door blocking the downstairs? Why the fuck not?
4. The entire downstairs could be sound proofed yet they stick the baby in a sound proof box? Stupid.
5. The whole hearing aid frequency thing is stupid when she just blows it's head off at the end. They make out it was easier to kill becasue she messed with it's hearing yet they all pause and open their head up to detect prey - head shot FUCKING BOOM!
6. Every single bad thing that happened was a result of the kids not doing what they are told and being fucking retards.
7. The kid could have released the hand brake on the care earlier.
8 The father goes out screaming like a bitch instead of swinging that axe like a man and potentially winning the fight or at least inuring it. Stupid - Again.
9. They relied on fireworks they had to run and light rather than a simpler method to make noise like a long line to the house that set off an alarm etc - they had electricity....
10. Why not set traps to dissuade them coming in or as early warning in the fields etc?
11. The stupidest thing is again the whole head opening BS. It made the whole rest of the story unbelievable as these things would have been wiped out in short order by gun toting citizens and the police/military.

Cheap jump scares but real genuine scares or horror...

Comment:
Probably will be a decent movie, don't particularly care, but, IF sound is the main plot point, they sure dropped the ball on it. ANY creature that hunts based on sound can and will hunt at frequencies and sound levels our human ears can't even compute to begin with. So not making noise...when every action you make = sound...
Like, why are they clothed? Why aren't their faces covered in silk cloths? Why don't they live in houses with active noise canceling? 
WHY is a beast that HUNTS on SOUND alive? When the US military has machines and devices that can kill someone with sound alone?

It makes no sense, and because of that, it's a load of bullshit.

In 2018, a writer of movies doesn't know you can kill a living being with sound...and that's pathetic.

Comment: O.k., just got back from watching The Quiet Place.  I went to the first morning showing, and besides my sweetie, his sister and 2 guys I didn't know, the theater was empty.  Nice, like a privaate showing:)  To tell the truth, I was pretty disappointed in this movie.  It could use work, a lot of work.  There are some things that go unanswered and some things that are just plain stupid. Not going to say anything and ruin it for others, but when you see it, you'll know.  It needs a lot of tweaking and someone in this group had an alternate ending that they made up, which I think is way better than the one here.  I'm a horror movie fan, and this one certainly did have parts that made me cringe and some that made me jump out of my chair.  One thing I hate in movies, any movie, is stupid women.  Why they make women stupid is beyond me, women aren't stupid at all.  If you go, go to a morning or afternoon matinee showing when it's cheaper.  Don't wait for the video to come out, it needs the big screen.  I'd generously give it 3 out of 5 stars.  Oh, we did get popcorn:)

Comment: This is one of the best suspenseful horror movies that has come out in a long time. I knew this movie was going to be good, but I was not expecting amazing. This movie had me at the edge of my seat and most horror movies don‚Äôt do that it also scared me a couple of times which also horror movies don‚Äôt do for me so I have to give this one a lot of praise because it does such that. The acting in this movie is phenomenal, the story is awesome and the special effects are great. I loved how the creatures looked something you have not seen much of and the way you have to be quiet or they can hear you. SPOILER: I thought that the birth scene was the most intense scene in the whole movie. There is no way a woman can be quiet giving birth to a baby and why would you even bring a child into that kind of world. I also thought that the creatures advantage was also its weakness that was cool, and when the dad died I choked up that scene was sad. The only thing I did not like was the ending come on, oh well it is still a great film. If you have not seen this movie then I recommend you do. This movie is Cinematastic rating 5/5

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Just watched this movie and I can't believe anyone likes this piece of shit. Instead of tension or suspense I just felt uncomfortable throughout the whole first act from the lack of dialogue (and I mean none) and sound in general.  I could hear people around me chewing and breathing in the cinema.

The creature is just an obvious rip off of Venom from spider man.  Looks almost the same and even has a similar weakness, which as far as I can tell is.... feedback?? WTF?  Never mind the fact that any creature with such advanced hearing should be able to hear the main chicks heart beating when it is right next to her at one point with no other sound around them. 

Several possibly interesting ideas were presented and then ignored.  Like how does a deaf kid, who we have to presume has always been deaf, even know when she is making noise?  What would that be like?  How would her experience differ from her families experience living in a silent world? Nope not interested.

 I also find it next to impossible that any human being could be completely silent for so long.  Everyone needs to vent vocally and loudly from time to time from frustration and anger, and the waterfall scene would have been a good time to explore that.  Nope.  

Sorry those two kids who fell into a grain silo are dead within minutes and one is never pulling the other out from under all that corn.

Through out the whole film I was just  asking "why?"  Like why not whisper in each others ears from time to time?  Why does a gunshot bring out all the creatures but a fucking rocket and fireworks only alert the one in the immediate vicinity?  Why is a new born baby next to silent the whole time?  Does he already know the situation?  Who were the other people lighting fires near the middle of the movie?  Why was a creature, said to be indestructible in news papers, suddenly vulnerable when its ears hurt?  Why was the lead male so shit at acting?  Why would a quality actress like Blunt sign up for such a piece of shit?  Why do I still hope Hollywood is capable of making good horror and suspense films anymore?

 I realize movies deserve some leeway when they are making fantasy films but this movie is just one frustrating piece of garbage in my opinion.

Comment:
Just watched this movie and, my gosh, it was a great experience. Totally worth the pay. The build up was good, I was constantly on edge during the movie. There are parts that actually touched my heart, made me shed a few tears. Above all, I love it that we actually get a good view of the creatures in this movie, not just glimpses and jump scares.

Also, I don't know whose idea it was but our local cinema did not play the usual ads or notice before the movie begun so the atmosphere was already set for the movie goers. Good job, SM.

Comment:
Just came from seeing this movie. This has to be one of the dumbest movies to be added with all the other dumbest movie made.
No back story as to where these creatures came from. 
Could not figure out why would you not be wearing any shoes what so ever. Not all shoes make noise.
So these creatures could hear anything from about 10 miles away ( give or take a few miles) which made no sense at all. They could travel long distances in a blink of a eye.
They attacked anything that made a noise that was what I guess from the movie, a normal decible sound.
I had to sit through this movie just to know how it ended and of course you can impair them with what else, high decibel sounds. Go figure.
I guess the people that made this thing think we the audience have no brains.
And the fact that our Military could not outwit these things and force them out in the open to kill them, that was just ass backwards to me.
Not a good movie for someone that has a brain and likes to get involved in to the storyline.
There were some good parts in it I have to be honest.
First part was the begining, and the last part as well. Everything else inbetween, dumb.

Comment: This movie was terrible and made no sense.  Plot holes galore!  1:  Move the family next to the waterfall and camp there!  PROBLEMS SOLVED!  2:  The nail was pointing UP from the step?  The laundry bag got caught on THE HEAD OF THE NAIL.  That means the nail would be pointing DOWN and the BLUNT end of the nail would be up.  3:  The monsters are so dumb they can be fooled by a KITCHEN TIMER, but you can't set traps or distractions for them?  4:  From where are they getting their endless supply of electricity to run all the lights and the tech lab in the basement?  And if they have so much electrical power, and the dad is so clever with electronics, how about rigging up some noise makers to mask your sounds?  Or at least distract the monsters?  5: You have two surviving children to look after, but you decide to have a baby which will do nothing but poop and MAKE NOISE.  And the plan was to let it live its miserable short life inside a BOX?  Good god this movie was stupid.  I hated it.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Though the idea is cool and the creatures look incredible,  all of it makes no sense. they cant be that much of a danger to anyone if all they hunt with is sound....  you could literally yell out and run 5 feet in any direction and stand still, they would not find you at all...  hence killing these creatures should be easy as fuck, dig big ass bear pits , yell and these blind creatures would just run in  and fall to their deaths..  at the ending of the movie the dad had soooo many oppertunity to save himself and his kids... he had a flashlight in his hands... throw it away in the grass, it makes sound, the creature will go for it...  hell instead they go for the truck and they make it to the truck  , all they had to do was to pull the handbreak and the truck would roll offhill on its own, - the creature would have been on that truck like there was no tomorrow... and they all would have lived happely ever after... it totaly breaks the movie...
 - there is a reason why animals on earth have more than one sense to use... eyesight - very important, cuzz it helps to see where you are going, hearing helps to locate prey hidden from SIGHT, smelling, tasting, feeling.  - these blind aliens or whatever they are could not wipe out humanity even if they tried. - UNLESS their hearing was sooooooooo good they could actually hear your heart beat, your blood flow,  every sound and identify it for what it is instantly. if they could hear the wind and tell rather the wind is hitting a cliff or not,   then you would be in trouble... but if you can yell out and talk standing next to a waterfall, then well, their hearing is flawed, their weakness is being blind... you could have them run off a cliff ... xD. that's what annoyed me about this movie - it is a great looking monster that is essentially flawed as fuck.  and the movie expects you to believe they are nigh invincible... when all you really have to do to kill em all is lure them into a trap with sound... i mean, that is why the movie completely sucks imo.  though like i said, great idea, great monster design, - just not thought out. and that some high end frequency takes em down is just another big ass mistake...you'd think the military , scientist would be able to freaking figure that out... an alien depending on its over evolved ears to live would thus be suseptible to way to much noize

SPOILER ALERT:






Hi if you are reading and you haven‚Äôt watched it GET OUT OF HERE AND SEE THE MOVIE and if you have seen it let‚Äôs have a talk!

This is tbh the only horror film that I cried in! Then when the boy died it was really freaking sad. Aside from that I was going to look away for a bit but I couldn‚Äôt resist watching it, I knew something scary was coming but I just couldn‚Äôt look away. (Also when the raccoon got smushed I jumped) 

An annoying thing was that at least 50% of the movie was quiet so when a loud noise came it scared the heck out of me. But it wasn‚Äôt that bothering because hey! It‚Äôs a horror film! 

Overall the movie was amazing and I clearly see why this was rated so good. Tbh I thought this was gonna be another one of those ‚Äúhorror films‚Äù that didn‚Äôt do so well but I really thought this was different and very clever. There aren‚Äôt many jump scares it‚Äôs just more like sudden sounds. And yah 10 out of 10, 5 stars, 100%, whatever you wanna say, I freaking loved this movie!

Chemtrail Challenge #3 - Blue Skies Anyone? (I Want My Blue Skies Back!!)

Look up any time of the day during daylight hours - morning/early afternoon/afternoon/early evening/evening.  See if you can ever see real, true, blue skies they way we used to have 20 or 30 years ago when there was actual "blue" blue skies instead of the very pale, very light blue covered with the thin layer of white gauze that now passes for "blue skies" and the long, stretched lines of faded, thin, wispy white that now passes for clouds.

 

Note down every day how many times you saw real blue skies over your head and the beautiful, brilliant, gorgeous sky-blue blue skies we used to enjoy.  Tally your results at the end of the month and post to your social media sites.  Ask your followers to do the same and to repost your results as well.  Let the Challenge begin and continue!

Comment:
John Krasinski has achieved Hitchcock level awesomeness! Hands down the most fun I've had at the movies in years.... And in the spirit of 'How it should have ended' I present to you my personal version of the ending of 'A Quiet Place' below - ***spoilers*** ***spoilers*** 

The terrifying creature leaps from the top of the truck to attack the father. As the creature is in mid air, a huge explosion is heard as the creature blows up into 1,000 bits. From the smoke and haze of the explosion a figure appears. It's a man with apocalyptic clothing and gear and a giant gun with smoke emanating from the barrel. He is wearing a dirty cloth wrapped around his face with goggles. He slowly removes it to expose his face. The father looks up, dumbfounded and says with astonishment 'Dwight??' The man says confidently...'That creature is the most dangerous animal on the planet. FALSE!...I AM!' The family is saved. The End

I like the movie a lot, but I have a couple of questions (WARNING: SPOILERS)....





If the creatures are blind, wouldn't that inhibit their movement? They walked down stairs without a problem, and navigated down narrow halls, etc. Unless they use their hearing to echo sound off walks, etc., they would inevitably stumble into many things.

The pregnancy COULD have been an accident, but if the parents know sound kills, then why bring a baby into the world?

Aside from these minor questions though, I thought it was a really good, unique movie.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Spoiler alert:





So this movie was definitely original. I thought it was enjoyable to a degree. The parts of the movie that were shown were enjoyable but I have 3 complaints. 
1. Way to short. The movie was barely an hour long and they definitely had room to fill.
2. Lack of a proper introduction. The movie starts 3 months into the ‚Äúinvasion.‚Äù Then jumped past a year. There is very little back story to what happened or where they came from. They do explain a bit in the newspapers but not many people will be able to read all of it while in theaters. They could have taken an extra 10 min with just a minor background.
3. The ending was god awful. They set up the conclusion so well. They found the weakness and later found out that they could be killed. Instead the dad died and the movie ends right before an epic battle. 

This movie had potential and as much as I want to like it, I can‚Äôt say I do. Would I watch it again? No. Would I recommend it? No.

Comment: 5 out of 10. This is not a horror movie. It is not scary. It's a drama, you'll see the giant bat/spider things like 4 times. No actual killing or maiming will be seen.  It's a silent film just not in black and white. Since I don't know sign language it would have been nice to have subtitles. If the little boy has been living in silence for 89 days why would he even consider turning on the toy rocket ship? He knew they were being quiet for a reason. Who decides to get pregnant during an apocalypse??? If you have be quiet to survive wouldn't a newborn defeat that purpose all they do is cry. No one saw that giant nail sticking out of the stairs? If they can't hear you when you're by the waterfall why didn't you just live there? Sighs. Idk why they are hyping this movie up and lying to people. If this movie scares you, I highly suggest you don't watch goosebumps or are you afraid of the dark. Those will give you nightmares. I love horror movies, and this wasn't an awful movie but it wasn't great as its been hyped up to be. I waited 4 months to see this, so excited only to be extremely disappointed. Now to wait for Hereditary.

Comment:
Pause at 0:06

The whiteboard on the right confirms something: 

The monsters are Blind and are attracted to sound. 
They don't eat their kill, for some reason.
Humanity has not found out their weakness, apparently.
The "How many -3- 5" is probably the number of monsters they have seen up close, or maybe the deaths of other people.

The newspapers classify the monsters as "death angels" or "dark angels", probably given by their slender bug-like shape and dark-grey color.
There might be more easter eggs, but these are all I've come up with.

Edit: Okay people, I haven't seen the movie yet. So please don't spoil things for me.

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Hooollllldddd on a second here! I have a LOT to say so read at your own risk.

Whoever gave the little boy that airplane thingy, that needed BATTERES was freaking stupid. And his parents let him keep it?! In one Scene you see the little boy playing with the toy, look carefully. You see the father carrying one kid, and then the mother had the daughter, and then the boy with the toy. That's five ppl. And in the rest of the trailer, you see only 4 ppl. So I'll bet you HE died.

Also, What if you sneez? Or fart? Or get sick? You just DIE instantly? Lol, I already hear the ppl in the theater smacking, and crunching, and russling, they're popcorn bags. Ugh üòí

Howwww is the mother going to have a KID without screaming in pain? I think there's no way that will happen, so it's safe to assume she dies too.

"What about the baby?" Asked some of you. Probably. What if there was an exciting twist where the baby didn't cry?? And the monster adoptied him/her??? Okay, I'm getting too far ahead of myself, let's move on.

The Dad.... Smh. The Dad is SO wrong in all kinds of ways! How did he get the mom pregnant? (Lowkey we all know HOW but... üòâ) The Dad let the kid have that toy, and he (probably) dies! He gets the mom pregnant, and now Her AND the Baby (more than likely) die! He's gonna be all by himself by the end of the movie. And he Ain't finna start a NEW family! Cuz ain't no women in the World gonna marry a Man that lives in a haunted house! Unless he lies and says otherwise.

Now.... The big Guns. *bang* *bang* *I'm so stupid* The Monster. Idk what the heck this thing is! Why did it choose THIS family to haunt? Was the family just unlucky or is there ACTUALLY a story behind it? I guess I just gotta watch and see. üòâ

Welp, I think I covered everything. If you have any Questions please tell me and I'll tell my opinion. Thanks.

Comment: Millicent Simmonds who plays the girl Regan in the movie, is actually deaf in real life. The director said " I didn't want a non-deaf actress pretending to be deaf. Most importunely [sic] though, because a deaf actress would help my knowledge and my understanding of the situations tenfold. I wanted someone who lives it and who could teach me about it on set. Since the family communicates in American Sign Language to avoid sound." Simmonds helped teach ASL to her fellow actors. This fact is really interesting. Can't wait to see the movie

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment: This is from the YA Dystopian novel "In The After" by Demitria Lunetta. In the book a teenage girl tells how these creatures suddenly took over and destroyed life as we know it. They have extremely sensitive hearing and are also attracted to bright lights. Her parents are gone and she has to learn how to survive on her own and not become the next meal for the creatures. She finds a baby girl and she and Baby live in the basement of her home and they communicate through sign language. After six years Amy and Baby are rescued and taken to New Hope where survivers are brought. Everything seems to be wonderful but Amy gradually realizes that the humans might be worse than the creatures outside. There is a sequel to this book it is titled "In The End". Leave it to Hollywood to turn it into a typical horror movie. üòí You should read the books. All I will say next about the novels is, when you put the words "Research Scientists and Government" in the same sentence shit will soon hit the fan! üò®

Title: A Quiet Place (2018) - Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment: This is actually a really cool, interesting and genuinely frightening concept done with great execution so far. There's something about pure silence that creates a feeling of tension and unease, and if the movie plays its cards right it could easily teach the audience to associate the breaking of silence with danger in the movie, creating a feeling of tension and foreboding during silence and extreme fear and terror when it's broken. It's also really cool seeing the world this trailer presents, and how it shows the way the survivors of whatever mysterious apocalypse occurrd have adapted. It also really helps my impression of the movie that the trailer doesn't use any jumpscares or reveal the monster in the last frame or anything stupid like that (though it does have the overused cliche of trailers having a "beat" sound effect that's supposed to build tension but really just takes away from the atmosphere, which is why I prefer the other trailer where the quiet lasts longer a little more).

Comment:
I don't understand, why did he just randomly pull out the toy shuttle? Like, realistically he's aware of the whole "don't make a sound" situation otherwise they would've died months ago, but he just nonchalantly pulls it out and starts playing with it. He doesn't even look guilty while doing it. Does coughing/sneezing/farting still exist? What happens if you pee too loudly? Do babies still cry? Why did they think it was a good idea to have a baby? How do the monsters figure out the difference between human noises and noises caused by the wind/thunder/rain? How loud of a noise can you make? How did they properly convey to the children that they were not allowed to talk anymore without talking to them? Do the monsters have to be nearby to hear you? Are they able to stop themselves from making noises in their sleep? Why do they have a gun when the newspaper at 0:09 says that their neither bullets nor bombs can penetrate their armor? 0:16 how did he get there without making noise? 0:17 do campfires not make enough noise to attract the monsters? 0:24 does dumping out that sand not count as making noise? 

Please stop showing me this ad.
